JOHANNESBURG - President Jacob Zuma has given the go ahead for an inquiry into the South African Revenue Service (Sars). Finance Minister Malusi Gigaba says the probe will focus on improving revenue collection. It will also look into tax administration at the receiver of revenue. WATCH: SARS chief denies untoward relationship with Duduzane Zuma Last year Sars reported that revenues had decreased by nearly R51-billion.
	
	"I have approached the president for an urgent inquiry, the commissioner has been informed and is fully supportive and is willing to cooperate. The inquiry will be established soon and its details will be released. The inquiry will also help to assess what other factors are causing under collection of revenue and what steps need to be taken to improve its capacity to collect revenue," Gigaba says. eNCA